1
00:00:01,094 --> 00:00:04,778
Foundation Course 2, Talk 8, Karma.

2
00:00:06,801 --> 00:00:19,219
It is very important to remember when we are talking about karma and talking about how we suffer or enjoy things, not to make the mistake of believing that everything that happens to us, good or bad, is because of past actions we have done.

3
00:00:20,280 --> 00:00:23,946
The Buddha taught there were five general laws that govern the universe.

4
00:00:24,111 --> 00:00:31,969
Briefly, the arising and falling of all material things, nature itself, is governed by the caloric order, caloric here meaning energy.

5
00:00:32,689 --> 00:00:36,618
This law approximates to what we would call physics, chemistry and biology.

6
00:00:37,621 --> 00:00:44,414
Secondly, there is the law of germinal order, which is really part of the caloric order, but refers to the vegetable kingdom.

7
00:00:45,560 --> 00:00:50,985
Thirdly, there is the moral order, and this is the karma we're going to look at more deeply.

8
00:00:51,746 --> 00:00:56,372
Fourthly, there is the psychical order, which equates today with the whole area of psychology.

9
00:00:57,213 --> 00:01:07,686
And finally, the order of natural phenomena, both physical and mental, which points to a deeper level, the absolute truths of the universe, such as the inherent transitoriness of all things.

10
00:01:08,728 --> 00:01:17,021
In other words, human beings are born into a set of circumstances of which only one is the result of personal past and present moral actions.

11
00:01:17,822 --> 00:01:24,591
But the important thing is that our states of mind and wrong understandings are very much dependent on this law of karma.

12
00:01:25,793 --> 00:01:33,183
In other words, if we seek happiness and liberation from all suffering, it is the understanding of this law of karma that will give us the key.

13
00:01:33,737 --> 00:01:41,828
It would be more accurate to say that all these laws are working all the time and that within them is the effect of our own decision making.

14
00:01:43,090 --> 00:01:49,179
Remember, the Buddha said, Volition, O disciples, is what I call karma.

15
00:01:50,581 --> 00:02:00,775
Furthermore, it is because of these other laws plus the effects of all other people's actions that it is impossible to say what the effect of any one action will be.

16
00:02:01,430 --> 00:02:04,493
Often a person will mean well, but it all turns out wrongly.

17
00:02:05,174 --> 00:02:07,718
A surgeon means to cure the patient, but the patient dies.

18
00:02:08,719 --> 00:02:11,604
Sometimes we wish to do harm and something good turns up.

19
00:02:12,004 --> 00:02:14,508
We speak badly about someone and get the promotion.

20
00:02:16,751 --> 00:02:21,538
Here we shall be looking at the different classifications of karma and what they mean in our practice.

21
00:02:22,098 --> 00:02:30,069
We shall go further into understanding the mechanisms and see how and why people seem to get away with things or strike lucky.

22
00:02:30,336 --> 00:02:35,905
This will take us into the Buddhist cosmology, the six realms where rebirth can take place.

23
00:02:36,526 --> 00:02:39,409
But we shall see they are also just states of mind.

24
00:02:39,950 --> 00:02:46,340
And finally, we shall dig a little deeper and see how all this fits in with the idea of there being no self.

25
00:02:49,343 --> 00:02:58,217
Even though we do not have much control over the effects of our actions in the outside world, we can come to have total control of the world of the inner mind.

26
00:02:58,837 --> 00:03:01,122
This is a very important point to grasp.

27
00:03:01,141 --> 00:03:14,163
The Buddha taught that our personal suffering, the suffering within the mind, all its negative states, was caused by desire and attachment and the ensuing decisions that lead from these wrong views.

28
00:03:15,493 --> 00:03:20,278
In other words, if we want to end our suffering, the problem lies within us, not outside us.

29
00:03:21,199 --> 00:03:28,926
The task is to change our decisions towards the wholesome, and allow the mind to purify itself through the practice of vipassana insight meditation.

30
00:03:29,907 --> 00:03:44,201
So although we intend to do good, but unfortunate results arise, although we intend to do harm, but fortunate results arise, the fact is that these intentions go to condition the mind, and this mind keeps on acting in that conditioned habitual way.

31
00:03:44,181 --> 00:03:49,627
Eventually, circumstances around a person will begin to mirror the internal state of the mind.

32
00:03:50,508 --> 00:03:57,655
However, because of the complexities of any given situation, we can never tell what the result of any particular action will be.

33
00:03:57,716 --> 00:04:03,181
The Buddha says this very clearly in the Achintaya Sutta, Discourse on the Unthinkable.

34
00:04:04,763 --> 00:04:09,227
The results of an action are unthinkable, nor are they to be thought about.

35
00:04:09,747 --> 00:04:14,251
trying to work out the results would lead one to madness or frustration.

36
00:04:16,514 --> 00:04:27,824
Having said this, because of this internal mechanism in the mind, this self-conditioning through acts of will that keep on creating the same sort of actions, so it is that eventually situations build up around us.

37
00:04:28,886 --> 00:04:32,069
It is also taught that the effect of any action will eventually reach us.

38
00:04:33,089 --> 00:04:38,454
At this point, the teaching of karma does not make sense unless the concept of rebirth is introduced.

39
00:04:38,906 --> 00:04:45,317
Without this concept it would seem that people really do get away with murder and people really do suffer unjustly.

40
00:04:46,458 --> 00:04:55,011
Rebirth simply states that the mind which is constantly seeking satisfaction for its desires goes on doing so even after the physical death of the body.

41
00:04:56,192 --> 00:04:58,757
In Buddhism the body is one thing and the mind is another.

42
00:04:59,497 --> 00:05:03,783
The body is sustained by the mind and other physical factors such as food.

43
00:05:04,252 --> 00:05:08,019
When the body dies, the mind itself leaves and seeks elsewhere to be born.

44
00:05:08,860 --> 00:05:21,062
This discarnate entity, a rather ugly expression used these days by scientists to describe what happens in near-death experiences, is not a permanent soul or self or integral entity at all.

45
00:05:22,023 --> 00:05:25,249
It is all the five aggregates the Buddha talks of.

46
00:05:25,887 --> 00:05:29,735
It is an energy which needs the physical world to satisfy its desires.

47
00:05:30,357 --> 00:05:39,559
As we shall see later, there are realms of existence in Buddhism where there is just pure mind, but such minds are purified if only for a time of sensual pleasure.

48
00:05:41,226 --> 00:05:50,841
In the Maha-karma-vibhanga-sutta, the discourse on the great exposition of karma, the Buddha answers questions that arise out of four types of situations.

49
00:05:51,742 --> 00:05:56,591
There is the wrong-doer who ends up badly, and the wrong-doer who ends up happily.

50
00:05:57,291 --> 00:06:02,339
There is the good-doer who ends up happily, and the good-doer who ends up badly.

51
00:06:02,658 --> 00:06:06,088
In his day there were those who took up certain positions.

52
00:06:06,771 --> 00:06:10,564
Some said all wrongdoers ended up badly and eventually in hell.

53
00:06:11,326 --> 00:06:14,456
The same with the good doers, saving that they went to heaven.

54
00:06:16,072 --> 00:06:26,235
Now this actual discourse came about because a young monk, Samidi, got it all wrong and so misguided another ascetic of a different beliefs, a certain Pottaliputta.

55
00:06:27,136 --> 00:06:29,440
The questions had centered on what happens after death.

56
00:06:30,142 --> 00:06:34,992
Here is the Buddha making his teaching clear to Ananda, who brought the tale to the Buddha.

57
00:06:35,901 --> 00:06:51,636
Now Ananda, there is such a person who has killed living beings, taken what is not freely given, misconducted himself in sexual desires, spoken falsely, spoken maliciously, spoken coarsely, gossiped, was covetous, was ill-willed and had wrong view.

58
00:06:52,658 --> 00:06:54,702
These, of course, are the ten wrong actions.

59
00:06:55,139 --> 00:07:03,250
On the dissolution of the body after death, he reappears in the states of deprivation, in an unhappy destination, in perdition, in hell.

60
00:07:04,072 --> 00:07:18,091
But the unwholesome karma producing this suffering may have been done by him earlier, or the unwholesome karma producing this suffering may have been done by him later, or wrong view was undertaken and completed by him at the time of death.

61
00:07:18,072 --> 00:07:26,824
And this is why, on the dissolution of the body after death, he appeared in the states of deprivation, in an unhappy destination, in perdition, in hell.

62
00:07:27,704 --> 00:07:36,536
Since he has committed one of the ten wrong actions, he will feel the results of that here and now, or in the next rebirth, or in subsequent existence.

63
00:07:38,947 --> 00:07:49,627
So what the Buddha is saying here is that the effects of unwholesome deeds can be felt in subsequent lives after this, that indeed we may now be suffering consequences of deeds done in previous lives.

64
00:07:50,771 --> 00:07:54,819
One of the important points here is wrong view taken at the time of death.

65
00:07:55,721 --> 00:07:59,367
This brings us to the classification of karma according to function.

66
00:08:00,074 --> 00:08:09,964
The last conscious moment of this life will be the first consciousness of the next, and will, according to Buddhist psychology, be the main mental disposition throughout the next life.

67
00:08:10,906 --> 00:08:17,093
If someone dies with hate on the mind, that hateful state of mind will constitute the subconscious flow of the next life.

68
00:08:17,812 --> 00:08:23,819
Conversely, if one dies in peace or in joy, that will be the next life's subconscious stream.

69
00:08:25,387 --> 00:08:29,291
More important, it is that last thought that sets the place of rebirth.

70
00:08:30,153 --> 00:08:35,321
That last thought is not a haphazard thing, but will be the thought that carries the most karmic energy in the mind.

71
00:08:36,121 --> 00:08:41,229
If, for instance, you look back over today, you will see you will remember one or two distinct events.

72
00:08:42,149 --> 00:08:47,297
If you look back over the past week or month, you'll see there'll be just one or two memories that stand out.

73
00:08:48,118 --> 00:08:55,207
At death, it is believed that one memory will arise that will be the one action or event that is most important to the person.

74
00:08:55,558 --> 00:09:01,811
This last thought then sets a particular disposition in the mind which underpins a person's personality and character.

75
00:09:03,052 --> 00:09:08,503
Running along with this karmic vein are two other types of karma known as supportive and counteractive.

76
00:09:09,284 --> 00:09:13,331
So it is not as though the mind is totally dominated by this last thought.

77
00:09:13,395 --> 00:09:22,730
What is more, there may be what's known as destructive karma, which is a very strong force, previously lying latent, but which may arise once the conditions are conducive.

78
00:09:23,149 --> 00:09:25,774
This destroys the reproductive karma itself.

79
00:09:28,278 --> 00:09:32,745
A person, for instance, may in this life be generally happy, have a good job, a happy family.

80
00:09:33,985 --> 00:09:41,918
Her happy state of mind, her positive virtues outnumbering her vices, may all be a result of the underlying reproductive karma that may be one of peace.

81
00:09:42,927 --> 00:09:45,230
She has died in her last life in a peaceful way.

82
00:09:45,770 --> 00:09:53,640
In this life, this reproductive karma is supported by happy circumstances, such as born into a well-to-do family in a rich western country.

83
00:09:54,302 --> 00:10:02,471
The counteracted karma is that the prevailing sexism in society stops her from realizing her potential, stops her from building a successful career.

84
00:10:02,451 --> 00:10:06,421
Suddenly, in the midst of life, she is struck by a debilitating disease or fatal illness.

85
00:10:07,043 --> 00:10:13,778
Such an unfortunate happening may very well be the product of an earlier life's unwholesome deed now maturing in this fashion.

86
00:10:14,956 --> 00:10:19,361
Obviously such destructive karma does not arise for everyone, in fact for the majority.

87
00:10:20,163 --> 00:10:31,797
So from this classification of karma by function into reproductive, supportive, counteractive and destructive, we can see that it makes unravelling one's karma very complicated indeed.

88
00:10:32,498 --> 00:10:44,153
We simply don't know whether what we suffer or enjoy now is the karma coming to fruition which was done in the past life or lives, or whether it is the fruit of this life's endeavour.

89
00:10:45,769 --> 00:10:55,041
So it is that the Buddha in the discourse of the great exposition of karma goes on to say that an evil doer on the dissolution of the body may reappear in a happy destination.

90
00:10:56,121 --> 00:11:04,412
So with the good doer such a person may end up upon death either in a happy or unhappy situation depending on the death moment consciousness.

91
00:11:05,513 --> 00:11:07,335
For meditators this is a point to ponder.

92
00:11:08,216 --> 00:11:11,360
We may now be in a happy situation but things might change.

93
00:11:12,081 --> 00:11:13,903
How are we going to react?

94
00:11:14,052 --> 00:11:27,057
Perhaps we ought to remind ourselves every day that there may be karmic debts to pay, and that if it is so, we should remind ourselves of the law of karma and accept things just as they are, knowing that the debt will be repaid the quicker, the more we accept it.

95
00:11:27,999 --> 00:11:36,515
Knowing that the debt will be repaid, and we shall be freed of that karmic debt, and we will no longer suffer from the effects of that past unwholesome action.

96
00:11:37,238 --> 00:11:46,748
Indeed, there will come a time when all the sour fruits of past and wholesome actions have been suffered, and we are left simply with the results of our continuing wholesome deeds.

97
00:11:49,270 --> 00:11:56,798
Another way that karma is classified is by the different effects, and this leads us to understand the more psychological aspects of karma.

98
00:11:57,580 --> 00:12:03,886
Here, the reproductive karma is called death-proximate karma, and as already mentioned, determines the subconscious stream.

99
00:12:04,340 --> 00:12:09,828
Secondly, the Buddha taught that there were actions which produced certain results, and these he called weighty karma.

100
00:12:10,711 --> 00:12:16,379
On the negative side, which will surely lead a person to states of perdition or hell realms, are four actions.

101
00:12:16,980 --> 00:12:24,052
To kill one's mother or father, to kill an arahat, a saint, to wound a Buddha, or to create a schism in the Sangha.

102
00:12:25,078 --> 00:12:34,470
As far as lay people go, since Buddhas and Arahats are in short supply, and it's very difficult for lay people to create a schism in the Sangha, the message is, don't kill your mum and dad.

103
00:12:35,870 --> 00:12:43,440
On the wholesome side, any of the higher states of concentration, known as jhana, or any of the paths of insight, will effect a happy rebirth.

104
00:12:44,421 --> 00:12:48,304
The third type of karma is very important for meditators to grasp.

105
00:12:48,325 --> 00:12:52,470
It is known as habitual karma, all our habits of thought, speech and action.

106
00:12:53,361 --> 00:12:55,125
those things that are second nature to us.

107
00:12:55,926 --> 00:12:59,811
It's mostly these we struggle with in ordinary daily life and in our meditations.

108
00:13:01,212 --> 00:13:03,336
Habits have a lot of force within them.

109
00:13:03,777 --> 00:13:09,985
They are very difficult to break and root out, as anyone who has tried to break one knows, whether it's smoking or giving up the morning cup of tea.

110
00:13:11,347 --> 00:13:16,434
Our work is to make sure that we are undermining unwholesome habits and reinforcing wholesome ones.

111
00:13:16,995 --> 00:13:19,740
This is, in fact, the right effort on the Noble Eightfold Path.

112
00:13:21,442 --> 00:13:33,621
In the context of long-term karma, meaning future rebirth, this now becomes even more important, for after weighty karma, it is usually this sort of habitual thought that we grasp for when life begins to pass from us.

113
00:13:34,663 --> 00:13:48,225
You can see there is a vast difference of mind between one that is in confusion demanding alcohol after a lifetime devoted to the bottle, and one demanding peace or friendships of good companion, or dare I say the quiet of a meditation room.

114
00:13:49,386 --> 00:13:55,730
Of course, ideally, now we are meditators, we should maintain our mindfulness, alert and awake, even unto that dying moment.

115
00:13:56,452 --> 00:14:00,206
That's what all this practice is about, to be able to die in meditation.

116
00:14:01,283 --> 00:14:03,907
The final classification is really potluck.

117
00:14:04,548 --> 00:14:05,971
It's known as stored-up karma.

118
00:14:06,731 --> 00:14:09,056
It includes light or rarely performed actions.

119
00:14:09,576 --> 00:14:13,823
However, depending on what one does, the force of such karma could be very great.

120
00:14:14,445 --> 00:14:17,048
That one explosion of anger that leads to a murderous blow.

121
00:14:17,068 --> 00:14:22,076
That one insight into the suffering of another that led to giving away a fortune.

122
00:14:23,169 --> 00:14:30,480
In daily life we must be wary of any new unwholesome thoughts, speech and action, for such things can grow into habits.

123
00:14:31,182 --> 00:14:35,307
Therefore we need to be ever vigilant, not to reinforce anything unskilful.

124
00:14:36,470 --> 00:14:42,018
We go out for a drink, we're invited again, and again, suddenly we're in the company of drinkers.

125
00:14:42,678 --> 00:14:44,402
Before we know it, we've got a problem.

126
00:14:47,081 --> 00:14:49,605
So now we've looked at karma in terms of a wider field.

127
00:14:49,865 --> 00:15:03,886
We see that the Buddha teaches not simply in the perspective of one life in which we either sink or swim, but a sequence of lives in which we hopefully become more and more aware of our ultimate purpose, more and more aware of the trap we are in and of the way to escape it.

128
00:15:04,788 --> 00:15:07,611
We see there are forces at play outside our personal karma.

129
00:15:08,293 --> 00:15:10,996
We see our own karma to be a very complicated thing.

130
00:15:11,787 --> 00:15:19,366
Different forces of karma may be playing different functions, sometimes supporting, sometimes counteracting the basic karma we were born with.

131
00:15:20,208 --> 00:15:26,927
We can see that what we have done and what we do has had and will have certain results.

132
00:15:27,768 --> 00:15:42,764
In this very complicated picture can we reduce everything to an easier view that will eventually bring us the desired results of happiness and liberation, such results that will lead to situations conducive for training and insight and the realization of the ultimate truth.

133
00:15:44,885 --> 00:15:50,312
The first is to ponder the fact that we own our own karma, we reap its results.

134
00:15:51,251 --> 00:15:54,635
There is a verse of the Buddha from the Dhammapada which brings this home to us.

135
00:15:56,455 --> 00:16:04,370
I am the owner of my karma, heir of my karma, born of my karma, related to my karma.

136
00:16:05,232 --> 00:16:07,557
I abide supported by my karma.

137
00:16:08,018 --> 00:16:13,889
Whatever I do, be it wholesome or unwholesome, I shall be heir to the results of that action.

138
00:16:15,793 --> 00:16:17,258
Karma is usually read as bad.

139
00:16:17,658 --> 00:16:19,543
We must correct this lopsided view.

140
00:16:19,844 --> 00:16:22,009
Karma is good so long as we behave skillfully.

141
00:16:22,890 --> 00:16:32,875
No matter how I read that verse, however, because of the preconceived idea that karma is some predetermined hard-to-bear fate, it's hard to see that in fact it is a message of hope.

142
00:16:33,378 --> 00:16:35,883
What it's saying is that we are in control.

143
00:16:36,644 --> 00:16:40,432
All right, the Buddha is no saviour that's going to let us off the hook.

144
00:16:40,451 --> 00:16:46,684
All right, the Buddha declared there is no merciful God we can appeal to with mitigating circumstances to alleviate our problems.

145
00:16:47,767 --> 00:16:54,340
But there is an obvious ending to all our suffering once we cotton on to the fact that all we have to do is do good.

146
00:16:55,282 --> 00:17:09,326
If we were to do good and only good, from now on, to live in a completely harmless way from this instant onwards, we can say that what we suffer now and in the future is just the results of past unskillful action, and that they are in fact burning out.

147
00:17:10,207 --> 00:17:15,596
They are all coming to an end, and we can look to a future where the fruits of our good actions will ripen.

148
00:17:16,657 --> 00:17:21,306
So it is that the Buddha enjoins us to gladden our hearts in the midst of our sufferings.

149
00:17:21,910 --> 00:17:30,618
He says, in fact, we are extremely fortunate to be born as human beings, for it is in this very human realm that we are most able to see the way out of our mess.

150
00:17:33,201 --> 00:17:36,465
This brings us to the teaching of the different realms of existence in Buddhism.

151
00:17:37,626 --> 00:17:46,777
The realms are divided into four divisions, the happy states, the unhappy states, the realms of form, and the formless realms.

152
00:17:46,797 --> 00:17:48,558
The last two we can deal with quickly.

153
00:17:49,400 --> 00:17:56,028
They are realms into which beings are reborn who have achieved the higher states of mind brought about by concentration meditation.

154
00:17:57,048 --> 00:18:00,314
They are highly blissful realms and life seems to be astronomically long.

155
00:18:01,174 --> 00:18:09,224
But like all realms in Buddhism they are impermanent and at some time or other beings fall from that existence into lower or maybe higher ones.

156
00:18:10,987 --> 00:18:17,634
Because life is so pleasurable in these realms beings are said to find it hard to train spiritually so content and happy are they.

157
00:18:18,458 --> 00:18:25,692
These realms need not concern us here, since to practice the jhana meditations is often beyond the ability of meditators who are too busy trying to earn a living.

158
00:18:26,996 --> 00:18:32,508
But if you really want to develop these states, you'll have to give yourself totally to the job, or join a monastery.

159
00:18:34,913 --> 00:18:38,661
It is the other two states, happy and unhappy, that concern us most.

160
00:18:38,792 --> 00:18:40,154
There are four unhappy realms.

161
00:18:40,734 --> 00:18:52,690
They are the different hell states, the animal realm, the hungry ghost states known as the paters, and the asura realm, which simply means that beings don't shine, a glum sort of existence.

162
00:18:54,392 --> 00:19:05,526
Because of our unwholesome deeds, then, a being can be reborn in states of fierce suffering, or as an animal, or as a discarnate entity, wandering about looking for satisfaction.

163
00:19:05,776 --> 00:19:09,280
The paters are said to live on this earth and approximate to our idea of ghosts.

164
00:19:10,241 --> 00:19:17,612
The happy realms include six different heavenly states, all of which are said to be most delightful, and life there seems to be very long.

165
00:19:18,251 --> 00:19:22,298
But most interestingly, the human realm is classified as happy.

166
00:19:24,480 --> 00:19:29,386
To understand this, we have to remind ourselves that all these realms refer also to states of mind.

167
00:19:30,109 --> 00:19:34,957
Whether or not to believe that other realms exist is left up to the individual in Buddhism.

168
00:19:35,739 --> 00:19:43,009
I met a Sri Lankan scholar who said he had proved beyond doubt that they were all metaphor symbolic for states of mind, that they didn't really exist.

169
00:19:43,871 --> 00:19:48,478
But my own reading of the scriptures leads me to believe that the Buddha did teach such realms as real.

170
00:19:49,519 --> 00:19:57,230
Of course, belief in such things is not necessary for insight, and anyway, all these realms suffer from the same problem of transiency.

171
00:19:57,650 --> 00:20:03,395
Even so, if doubt comes to the mind, it's simply best to give it the benefit of the doubt until proved otherwise.

172
00:20:04,056 --> 00:20:08,500
There's no harm either way, believing or not believing, and it may just turn out to be true.

173
00:20:10,903 --> 00:20:15,528
Since these states are all states of mind, they can be experienced here in the human realm.

174
00:20:16,229 --> 00:20:21,012
When a person suffers from a deep depression or indeed a mental illness, this is akin to a health state.

175
00:20:21,794 --> 00:20:27,640
When a person is drunk and his intelligence and will are very much reduced, it is akin to an animal state.

176
00:20:28,057 --> 00:20:38,214
When a person is controlled by an obsession, this is a Peta, a hungry ghost, often portrayed with a big belly and a tiny mouth to suggest their inability to achieve satisfaction.

177
00:20:39,557 --> 00:20:42,702
When we are generally unhappy, we are Azuras, lacking gladness.

178
00:20:43,505 --> 00:20:46,869
When we are happy, joyful, excited and so on, we are in the heavenly realms.

179
00:20:47,511 --> 00:20:51,298
Inhabitants there are known as Devas, usually translated as gods.

180
00:20:52,882 --> 00:20:58,250
We can also experience all the realms of form and the formless realms through concentration meditation.

181
00:20:58,891 --> 00:21:03,317
In other words, as humans, we have the capacity to experience all states of mind.

182
00:21:03,959 --> 00:21:09,607
That's why this earth is a very special place to be, and Tibetan Buddhism calls it a precious birth.

183
00:21:10,583 --> 00:21:17,573
Here we are not crushed by unhappiness, nor is our intelligence dulled, nor are we lost in pleasure and happy states of mind.

184
00:21:18,252 --> 00:21:19,836
In fact, we experience them all.

185
00:21:20,616 --> 00:21:23,359
We experience the despair of hell and the joys of heaven.

186
00:21:24,080 --> 00:21:29,328
This mental wandering about can bring us great wisdom once we begin to see things with right understanding.

187
00:21:30,490 --> 00:21:39,982
In the human realm we can experience that characteristic of all existence more keenly, the transiency and the endless unsatisfying search for happiness and contentment.

188
00:21:41,042 --> 00:21:52,902
Of course there are human beings who are living in desperate circumstances, some who are born with very low intellectual capacity, others who live like gods, but the vast majority have the ability to see the ultimate truths within all this becoming.

189
00:21:53,623 --> 00:21:57,730
Knowing this, we must take advantage of this life to develop in virtue and wisdom.

190
00:21:59,692 --> 00:22:02,156
I've covered a great deal here, so I'd better recap.

191
00:22:03,250 --> 00:22:10,958
I started by recalling the law of karma, the importance of the will, and the reciprocal nature whereby good returns good and harm returns harm.

192
00:22:11,959 --> 00:22:17,184
However, we can't put everything that happens to us in the world down to our own personal past and present actions.

193
00:22:17,865 --> 00:22:19,728
There are other laws and other people.

194
00:22:20,588 --> 00:22:26,575
But essentially, when it comes to the third noble truth, the end of suffering, we're talking about the world within us.

195
00:22:27,144 --> 00:22:30,708
However, even if this is true, our actions do have effect.

196
00:22:31,087 --> 00:22:35,551
We will reap sweet or sour fruits in future rebirths, if not in this present life.

197
00:22:37,493 --> 00:22:49,144
Talking of rebirth, we saw the mechanisms of reproductive karma and death proximate karma to show how actions in the past life condition the last death consciousness, which in turn is a subconscious stream of the next life.

198
00:22:50,525 --> 00:22:56,190
This karmic strain is either helped by supportive karma or undermined by counteractive karma.

199
00:22:56,811 --> 00:23:00,236
This doesn't mean that counteractive karma is always unwholesome.

200
00:23:00,256 --> 00:23:02,258
It depends on the death proximate karma.

201
00:23:03,640 --> 00:23:10,728
For instance, there was a great Buddhist leader in India, Dr. Ambedkar, who was born in very undesirable circumstances as an untouchable.

202
00:23:11,367 --> 00:23:14,352
But the Maharaja took interest in him, counteractive karma.

203
00:23:15,071 --> 00:23:19,237
He ended up with high degrees from Oxford and being called the father of the Indian constitution.

204
00:23:20,838 --> 00:23:25,384
Finally, there is the destructive karma, which explains why catastrophes can happen to us.

205
00:23:26,596 --> 00:23:27,938
This is how karma functions.

206
00:23:28,959 --> 00:23:39,234
The classification by effect pointed out that there are certain actions which bring sure results either to be born in the realms of dire suffering or in the realms of form or formless realms.

207
00:23:40,435 --> 00:23:45,163
There is stored up karma which indeed may contain the destructive karma mentioned above.

208
00:23:46,265 --> 00:23:55,117
Most important for us meditators is habitual karma for these tend to be most troublesome to us if unwholesome and most beneficial if wholesome.

209
00:23:56,194 --> 00:24:04,211
This led to the different realms in Buddhism with the accent firmly on the importance of the human realm as being the place most conducive for our liberation.

210
00:24:06,335 --> 00:24:13,950
Finally, I would like to go a little deeper and point to the importance of vipassana insight meditation and the meditative lifestyle in general.

211
00:24:15,009 --> 00:24:30,269
When we are meditating on the breath and noticing its passing nature, we are also beginning to grasp that other characteristic of the human being, namely that this body and mind, this karma, do not constitute a complete entity, a substantial ego, a soul, a person or a self.

212
00:24:31,112 --> 00:24:32,973
The human is a collection of parts.

213
00:24:33,996 --> 00:24:41,085
When pain comes to us in the meditation, this should be greeted with open arms, for what pain does most wonderfully is concentrate the mind.

214
00:24:42,314 --> 00:24:49,564
When pain arises in the knees from the posture, for example, how easy it is for us to keep our attention on it, but we must observe it with wisdom.

215
00:24:50,325 --> 00:24:58,855
We have to catch all the passing reactions to it, the fear, the aversion, and we must keep bringing the awareness back to some observing the sensations.

216
00:25:00,699 --> 00:25:05,204
At some point, the pain will be experienced as just sensation, pure sensation.

217
00:25:05,885 --> 00:25:07,047
All the labelling will have gone.

218
00:25:07,928 --> 00:25:12,034
The meditator knows only the arising and falling of minute moments of sensation.

219
00:25:12,875 --> 00:25:21,608
With this sort of concentrative awareness, the meditator comes to realize that the sensations, the so-called pain, are one thing, and the consciousness that knows it another.

220
00:25:22,371 --> 00:25:24,875
In other words, the sensations are not the consciousness.

221
00:25:25,635 --> 00:25:27,659
This consciousness itself does not suffer.

222
00:25:28,661 --> 00:25:35,372
At such deep points of concentration, there is not even the awareness of someone, or a person, or a soul, or a self that is knowing.

223
00:25:36,517 --> 00:25:43,465
Whenever that knowing faculty identifies with the labeling, it is pain, then it becomes the aggregate of perception, an ego is born.

224
00:25:44,247 --> 00:25:53,278
When that knowing faculty identifies with all the reactions, I'm afraid, I'm anxious, it becomes the aggregate of volitional formations, and an ego, a self, a person, is born.

225
00:25:54,680 --> 00:26:02,710
So long as there is an iota of a self, or a feeling of somebody observing, so long is there an ego, a person, a soul, or a self.

226
00:26:03,471 --> 00:26:05,173
This, of course, has to be experienced.

227
00:26:05,473 --> 00:26:08,377
No words can catch this sort of experiential knowledge.

228
00:26:08,979 --> 00:26:12,564
It's like trying to describe the taste of a knowledge to someone who's never even seen one.

229
00:26:14,006 --> 00:26:23,778
But such experiences undermine a lot of wrong understanding, and the more we come to experience such things, the more the Buddha's teaching of anatta, non-self, becomes clear.

230
00:26:24,921 --> 00:26:33,792
As it becomes more and more clear, there is a growing realization that karma is just a force that manifests as the five aggregates, the khandha, the human being.

231
00:26:34,397 --> 00:26:47,296
that in fact humans are nothing but this karmic force, that is, form and energy, that the whole world is in fact just this form, this energy, this karma, that none of it constitutes anything substantial.

232
00:26:48,877 --> 00:26:59,833
In The Path of Freedom, the spiritual classic written by Buddhaghosa, he says in a verse, There is no doer of a deed, nor is there anyone who reaps the deed's effects.

233
00:27:00,953 --> 00:27:03,577
Phenomena alone flow on and on,

234
00:27:04,164 --> 00:27:05,968
No other view than this is right.

235
00:27:07,971 --> 00:27:11,115
We can slowly come to realize all this in our meditation and daily life.

236
00:27:11,977 --> 00:27:17,084
When we know this totally, when we have this insight into all things, then, of course, we shall be enlightened.

237
00:27:17,505 --> 00:27:21,451
For what is it the Buddhas know we don't, if it isn't exactly this?

238
00:27:22,271 --> 00:27:29,903
That anything that arises and passes away does not constitute a person, a soul, a self, or any substantial being.

239
00:27:31,672 --> 00:27:34,096
then wherein lies our liberation, the taste of freedom?

240
00:27:34,838 --> 00:27:45,642
It is in the discovery, the realization for oneself, of that unborn, that unbecoming, that uncreated, that uncompounded, that makes this realization.

241
00:27:48,909 --> 00:27:51,054
I hope you found this talk interesting and helpful.

242
00:27:52,636 --> 00:27:54,039
May all of you be happy and peaceful.

243
00:27:54,682 --> 00:27:57,627
May all of you attain the Nibbanic peace within.

